 Description:
 The Family of Expeditionary Fuel Systems (FEFS) provides the full spectrum of fuel capabilities to support Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations (EABO), Littoral Operations in a Contested Environment
 (LOCE), and related Force Design requirements, including providing a partial spectrum fuel capability to support contact/blunt layer operations. It consists of principal end items and components that perform
 receiving, storage, analysis, sensing, metering, reporting distribution, and dispensing of fuel to ground and aviation assets. These systems can be organized to meet specific fuel mission requirements.

 The program provides materiel solutions that enable an expeditionary fuel foraging capability for contact/blunt layer operations through the procurement of the Expeditionary Mobile Fuel Additive Capability
 (EMFAC). This provides the ability to inject additives into commercial jet fuel to produce military-specification fuel, which increases the resiliency of the fuel supply chain. It also provides a modernized, portable,
 and expeditionary fuel analysis capability for both aviation and ground platforms through the consolidation of multiple testing kits into a portable Petroleum Enhanced Analysis Kit (PEAK). This enhances the
 future force's ability to conduct comprehensive fuel quality surveillance in support of distributed operations. The Marine Corps is participating in the Army's PEAK program and is subject to its scheduled events
 and milestones.

 Additionally, the program enhances support to distributed operations by disaggregating and modernizing large legacy Tactical Fuel Systems into tailored Expeditionary Fuel Dispensing Systems (EFDS). This
 transformation reduces storage requirements, improves accountability, and enhances deployment capability by providing organic, self-support refueling capability. These modernization efforts encompass
 comprehensive fuel management by using advanced material sensors and meters to track consumption through the Fuel Automated Reporting System (FARS); provide scalable, modular Beach Receiving Kits
 (BRKs) to synchronize with commercial and Navy over-the-shore fuel delivery platforms; optimize mobile fuel distribution via replacement of the Six Container (SIXCON) Pump Module to reduce operational
 footprint; and the Self-support Portable Distributed Refueling System (SPDRS) for small, distributed units. The program further enables aviation ground support by equipping Fleet units with the Tactical Aviation
 Ground Refueling System (TAGRS), which provides a highly mobile Forward Arming and Refueling Point (FARP) capability in support of EABO and LOCE operations.




