 Description:
 Air & Amphibious Support Equipment supports multiple capabilities, enhancements, life cycle replacements, and personnel equipment shortfalls when required, and as needed by reconnaissance units
 throughout operating forces for airborne and parachuting programs, and the amphibious surface and subsurface reconnaissance capability programs.

 Airborne Reconnaissance Equipment (ARE) includes individual parachuting equipment to be deployed by Marine Forces Special Operations Command (MARSOC) and the Marine Air Ground Task Force
 (MAGTF) Reconnaissance operations in support of Force Design. Systems include but are not limited to the next generation of Augmented Parachute System (APS-1) for increased operational flexibility, T-11
 Static Parachute, and Tandem Offset Resupply Delivery System (TORDS).

 Aerial Delivery (AD) Family of Systems provides capability for increased aircraft survivability, ground accuracy, and standoff delivery for airdrop missions. AD consist of the Joint Precision Airdrop System
 (JPADS) and the Cargo Parachutes Family of Systems. JPADS is a GPS-guided airdrop system that significantly enhances the Marine Corps aerial resupply capability. It delivers supplies with high accuracy
 from altitudes up to 24,500 feet, reducing exposure to ground threats. Adaptable to various payload sizes, JPADS also supports the Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations (EABO) concept, enabling rapid
 establishment and resupply of bases in contested areas. Cargo Parachutes includes the Extracted Container Delivery System (ExCDS), G-16 Parachute, and the G-15 Parachute. The ExCDS provides low-
 level high-speed air drop capability. The G-16 is a low velocity cargo parachute capable of delivering loads with a weight range of 2,500-42,000 pounds. The G-15 is a low velocity cargo parachute capable of
 delivering loads with a weight range of 401-2,200 pounds.

 Amphibious Reconnaissance Capability (ARC) is an overarching Family of Systems which sustains, enhances, and supports capabilities of current and future combatant diving systems, and small craft when
 required by the fleet. ARC includes: Enhanced - Combat Rubber Reconnaissance Craft (E-CRRC), ECRRC Non-Gasoline Burning Outboard Engine (NBOE), Open Water Safety Craft/Assault Amphibious Safety
 Boat (AASB), Sub-Surface Hydrographic Amphibious Reconnaissance Craft, Underwater Breathing Apparatus, Combatant Diver Full Face Mask, Combatant Diver Vest, Expeditionary Hyperbaric Chamber
 System, Transportable Recompression Chamber System, Combat Diver Dry Suit, Maritime Operations Suit, Portable Compressor Diesel Driven, Rapid Deployable Oxygen Transfer Pump System, Enhanced
 Diver Propulsion Device, Marine Individual Assault Kit, Marine Assault Breacher's Kit, and Full Spectrum Battle Equipment.

 Family of Organic Littoral Mobility and Distribution Systems (FOLMDS) provides flexible and scalable mobility and distribution means in littoral environments and encompasses both crewed and uncrewed
 watercraft as well as required supporting equipment necessary for their operation. These systems represent partial materiel solutions to Marine Corps Gap List (MCGL) gaps Conduct Multi-Domain Distribution
 and Material Handling, Shore-to-Shore Maneuver Platforms, and Autonomous Distribution and Intra EAB Sustainment. The FOLMDS includes but is not limited to the Autonomous Low-Profile Vessel, a low
 profile, low observable uncrewed surface vessel used for littoral materiel distribution.


