 Description:
 The Family of Field Medical Equipment (FFME) is the Marine Corps' program of record for organic expeditionary medical capability, comprising modular, scalable equipment sets that provide life-saving care
 across the full spectrum of Health Service Support (HSS) from point of injury through resuscitative surgery and patient evacuation. FFME capabilities are aligned to Marine Corps operational concepts such as
 Distributed Maritime Operations (DMO) and Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations (EABO), enabling flexible, rapidly deployable medical support in contested and communication-degraded environments
 through Authorized Medical Allowance Lists (AMALs) configured by clinical role, unit type, and mission profile.

 Family of Field Medical Equipment (FFME) is comprised of items such as:

 AMAL Modernization refreshes legacy medical assemblages to align with current clinical guidelines and battlefield care standards by addressing component obsolescence and integrating emerging technologies
 such as Expeditionary Medical Refrigeration Unit (EMRU), Portable Ruggedized Energy Efficient Medical Sterilizer (PREEMS), Intranasal Cooling for Encephalopathy Prevention, Expeditionary Portable Oxygen
 Generation System (EPOGS). It also addresses existing assemblages such as the Chemical Biological Incident Response Force (CBIRF), Geological Mission Hot and Cold Weather gear (GEO MISSION)
 equipment, and expeditionary tools (Individual First Aid Kits (IFAKs), Corpsman Assault Systems (CAS), Combat Lifesaver Systems (CLS)). This initiative also addresses increased stocking levels for enterprise
 readiness. Modernization requires integration across cybersecurity, configuration management, modeling, logistics, warehouse operations, and distribution. The goal is to align these modernized AMALs with
 operational plans (OPLANs), training and exercise requirements (TEEP), and Class VIIIa objectives.

 The Forward Resuscitative Surgery System (FRSS) is a highly mobile, rapidly deployable, modular trauma surgical unit that provides emergency surgical interventions to stabilize casualties who might otherwise
 succumb or lose limbs before reaching treatment. It's the lightest and most mobile Marine Corps HSS element for trauma surgical care, deployable by air or surface.

 The Battalion Aid Station (BAS) AMAL provides equipment for a BAS, delivering scalable, expeditionary initial resuscitative and stabilizing care for 50 surgical patients; includes rugged equipment for immediate
 pre-surgical resuscitation and stabilization in austere environments.

 The Sick Call AMAL equips medical personnel for 30 days to treat 300 deployed Marines and Sailors for Disease and Non-Battle Injuries (DNBI). Provides Level One HSS and can augment a BAS or deploy
 independently.




