 Description:
 Rolling Airframe Missile (RAM) is a high firepower missile system used to defeat Anti-Ship Missiles (ASMs), as well as other airborne threats. RAM is a surface-to-air missile with passive dual-mode radio
 frequency/infrared (RF/IR) guidance and an active-optical proximity and contact fuse. RAM has minimal shipboard control systems and is autonomous after launch. The RAM Block 1 incorporated "all-the-way-
 homing" to improve performance against evolving passive and active ASMs. The RAM Block 2 provides increased kinematic capability against highly maneuvering threats and improved RF detection against low
 probability of intercept threats. The RAM missile is fired from a RAM Guided Missile Launching System (GMLS) (MK-49), which holds 21 RAM rounds. RAM is also fired from the Close-In Weapon System (CIWS)
 SeaRAM Anti-Ship Missile Defense System (MK-15 MOD 31-33) which holds 11 rounds.

 The FY 2026 spend plan for Rolling Airframe Missile (RAM) included $122,372 thousand of discretionary and $18,000 thousand of mandatory funding for a total of $140,372 thousand. The mandatory funds
 enable the procurement of test equipment to establish a domestic seeker head production line for RAM BLK2B.

 Cooperative Agreement:
 RAM is a cooperative program with the Federal Republic of Germany. The U.S. and Federal Republic of Germany cooperatively produce Block 2 missiles, launchers, and Ordnance Alterations (ORDALTs). The
 Block 2 production Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) was signed on 19 March 2013. Amendment 3 to the Block 2 Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) was signed June 2025.




