 Description:
 The Weapons Industrial Facility (WIF) program supports the following NAVSEA and NAVAIR facilities within the Navy's Organic Industrial Base (OIB) for weapons: the active Naval Industrial Reserve Ordnance
 Plant (NIROP) Allegany Ballistics Laboratory (ABL) in Rocket Center, WV; the active Naval Surface Warfare Center Indian Head Division (NSWC IHD) in Indian Head, MD; the active Naval Air Warfare Center
 Weapons Division (NAWC WD China Lake) in China Lake, CA; and the inactive Naval Weapons Industrial Reserve Plant (NWIRP) in Bedford, MA. The budget provides funding for the Navy's weapons OIB
 to recapitalize and modernize aging plant infrastructure; enable process improvement to accelerate development, production, and support of weapon systems; resolve life, safety, and environmental issues;
 and enact immediate operational support of National Security needs. Capital rehabilitation projects within the Navy's weapons OIB support weapon systems such as Standard Missile (SM-2/6/3), Tomahawk
 Land Attack Missile (TLAM), Torpedoes, Mines, One-Way-Attack (OWA) systems, 2.75-inch rockets, Rolling Airframe Missile (RAM), Evolved Sea Sparrow Missile (ESSM), AIM-9X Sidewinder Missile, AIM-9M
 Sidewinder Missile, FMU-143 Penetrating Bomb Fuze System, Hellfire Missile, Guided Multiple-Launch Rocket System (GMLRS), Tomahawk, and Trident Gas Generators.

 FY 2027 includes investment in supply munitions bottlenecks. This funding addresses gaps in materials, hardware, and industrial base capacity. As the Navy looks to surge its organic industrial base along with
 the commercial industrial base, these investments will accelerate deliveries to the warfighter.

 [P5 / FU002 Capital Type Rehabilitation]: This program funds projects that eliminate environmental and safety deficiencies in compliance with local, state, and federal OSHA regulations. These regulations
 mandate requirements, which must be met if plant shuts down in order to avoid criminal liability, and severe financial penalties. The program also includes critical upgrades to maintain high liability areas such as
 fire and security systems, roofs, boilers, electrical distribution systems, bridge crane systems, and other structural repairs essential to maintain the industrial integrity of the plant. The funding will alleviate sub-
 tier component bottlenecks including safe and arm devices/igniters, propulsion systems, thermal batteries, airframes, control/motion/guidance systems, as well as plan and design for future surge capacity by
 integrating overlapping demand at component suppliers.




