Justification:
BACN includes the payload, its host platforms, and associated ground systems. As mandates/ requirements emerge for new hardware and software capabilities that improve system performance, external time
references, interoperability and open mission system technologies, BACN will host the integration of these and future emerging technologies, such as, but not limited to, Ka-Band Satellite Communications
(SATCOM), Supplemental Type Certs (STC), and M-Code Military Global Positioning System (GPS).

Funding supports program support costs including but not limited to, A&AS and assessments. The FY 2026 request was reduced by $0 for Advisory and Assistance Services to promote efficiencies and advance
the policies of the Administration in alignment with Executive Order 14222, "Implementing the President's Department of Government Efficiency Cost Efficiency Initiative.

Funding will be used to address Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS) issues and long lead procurement. This may include modifications required for enhanced capability and improvements to system
reliability and maintainability. Safety of flight considerations, including but not limited to, performance, aircraft structural integrity, availability, and continuity of service requirements for long range reference, local
area reference, and landing/ terminal reference.

Funding will also be used to procure a flight simulator to support aircrew currency, mission profile training, and reduce reliance on industry-provided platform training.

BACN aircraft platforms need to meet standardized avionics baseline and the production of all Supplemental Type Certificates of the most up to date configurations of the fleet. This effort includes Military GPS,
Advanced Position, Navigation, and Timing (PNT) systems, communication systems/capabilities and any additional mandates levied on the BACN system and platforms. Funding will also be used for fulfillment of
requirements in support of alteration, conversion, and modernization of the BACN fleet.

FY2026 funding will procure installation kits for both M-Code Military GPS and Multifunctional Information Distribution System Joint Tactical Radio System (MIDS JTRS) Block Upgrade 3 (BU3).

M-Code will provide significantly enhanced resilience against jamming and interference, reducing risks and ensuring continued aircraft and data link operational capability. This transition is mandated to replace
the vulnerable P/Y code with the more secure M-Code system. By enabling successful mission accomplishment even in contested electromagnetic environments, M-Code allows for the reliable distribution of
critical data under jamming conditions. This effort encompasses software development, integration, and deployment across all seven BACN aircraft. Each aircraft requires two M-Code units - one in the cockpit
and one within the payload. These units comprise an Embedded GPS Inertial Navigation (EGI), an Antenna Electronics Unit (AEU), and a Controlled Reception Pattern Antenna (CRPA). Six M-Code units will be
utilized during the Research and Development phase—two for the Global Express, two for the Global 6000, and two for additional test articles. The procurement phase will ultimately acquire 20 additional M-Code
units: two for each of the remaining five aircraft, plus ten spares, resulting in a total of 26 EGIs, 26 AEUs, and 16 CRPAs.

MIDS JTRS BU3 is an ongoing effort to incorporate mandated Link 16 modernization that modifies the current BACN weapon system's payload and software with MIDS JTRS BU3 terminals. This effort is
driven by mandates to ensure the BACN fleet is at the forefront of Link 16 advancements. The BU3 upgrade enhances data exchange speeds, improves network performance, and enables the handling of more
complex tactical information, such as advanced targeting data and real-time situational awareness. The first batch of terminals have been submitted for upgrade and there are five batches remaining. Batch
numbers are as follows (13, 10, 10, 10, 11, 7) for a total of 61 terminals.



