 Description:
 This line item funds modifications to the C-130H and Special Mission C-130 aircraft. The four-engine C-130H provides theater airlift and carries either 92 troops, 64 paratroopers, 74 litter patients, or six (6)
 standard 463-L pallets. The Air Force currently has 117 C-130Hs and 10 LC-130Hs, all operated by the Air National Guard and Air Reserve Component. These totals will drop to 61 C-130Hs and 10 LC-130Hs by
 2029 after accounting for all the C-130Js appropriated by Congress to date that have not yet delivered. The remaining C-130Hs at that time will range in age between 35-40 years old. However, Center Wing Box
 (CWB) replacements extend the C-130H service life into the 2100s. Additionally, modifications like Avionics Modernization Program (AMP) Increment 2 modernize the aircraft, keeping it viable for the foreseeable
 future.

 Funding provides weapon system modifications and upgrades to meet USAF mission requirements for the LC/C-130H fleets. FY 2026 primary efforts include: C-130 Avionics Modernization Program (AMP)
 Increment 2 (Exhibit 8515), Center Wing Box (CWB) replacement (Exhibit 8578), NP2000 8-Bladed Propeller (Exhibit 3773), and Low Cost Modifications (Exhibit 99999X).

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 Funding may be used to address Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS) issues.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in PE 0401115F.

 The FY 2026 request was reduced by $3.767 million for Advisory and Assistance Services to promote efficiencies and advance the policies of the Administration in alignment with Executive Order 14222,
